## Are Blue Nile Sapphires Real? Natural or Lab-Created?

**Blue Nile sapphires are natural stones, not lab-created.** This matters — lab sapphires exist and are significantly cheaper, but Blue Nile's sapphire ring catalog uses genuine earth-mined sapphires.

**Are they heat-treated?** Almost certainly yes — and this is completely normal and expected. Over 95% of all sapphires on the market are heat-treated to improve color saturation and clarity. This treatment is permanent, stable, and universally accepted in the fine jewelry industry. It does not affect value in any meaningful way for stones in this price range. If you want untreated "no heat" sapphires with certification, you're in a different market (typically $30,000+).

**What quality are they?** Blue Nile doesn't publish individual grading reports for their preset sapphire rings the way they do for diamonds. The sapphires are selected to match each setting — a 7x5mm oval will be eye-clean and appropriately colored for the price point. This is standard for preset colored gemstone jewelry across all reputable retailers.

---

## Blue vs Pink Sapphire: Which Should You Choose?

Sapphire is corundum (aluminum oxide). Pure corundum is colorless. Blue comes from iron and titanium traces; pink comes from chromium (the same element that makes rubies red — a pink sapphire and a ruby are the same mineral, just different color concentrations).

| | Blue Sapphire | Pink Sapphire |
|---|---|---|
| Color | Royal to cornflower to teal blue | Pale blush to vivid hot pink |
| Association | September birthstone, royalty, tradition | Romance, femininity, Kate Middleton alternative |
| Metal pairing | White gold, platinum | Rose gold, white gold |
| Price comparison | Comparable | Comparable at this quality level |
| Best occasion | Engagement ring, significant anniversary | Birthday, Valentine's, everyday wear |

**Blue sapphire** is the classic choice — the color of Princess Diana's ring, now Princess Catherine's. If you're buying a sapphire engagement ring or a September birthstone gift, blue is the right call.

**Pink sapphire** is warmer, more fashion-forward, and pairs beautifully with rose gold. It's the choice for someone who wants color jewelry that reads feminine rather than royal. Blue Nile's Riviera Pavé Pink Sapphire in 18K rose gold at $769 is exactly this energy.

