## Honest Criticism: What Blue Nile Gets Wrong on Sapphire Rings

**1. No sapphire quality information is published.** For diamond rings, Blue Nile gives you cut/color/clarity grades. For sapphire rings, you get the stone dimensions (7x5mm) and the metal, nothing else. You don't know whether the sapphire is heat-treated only or glass-filled, what the exact hue is, or how the color saturation ranks. This is industry-standard for preset colored stone jewelry — but it's worth knowing before you expect the same transparency as a diamond purchase.

**2. The 60% off JA deals create urgency that isn't explained.** Blue Nile lists several rings at 60% off without explaining why — it's the James Allen brand shutdown. These prices will normalize once the clearance period ends. If a 60% off deal interests you, don't sleep on it.

**3. Sapphire rings cannot be custom-configured the way diamonds can.** Blue Nile's diamond engagement rings let you choose your own stone and setting separately. For sapphire, you buy a preset ring — the stone is already selected. If you want a specific sapphire quality (unheated, Kashmir origin, specific hue), you need a custom jeweler, not Blue Nile.

